column58: Local Land Charges Programme
column59:
Following Royal Assent in February 2015, Land Registry will become the body responsible for providing a Local Land Charge service for England. Local Land Charges records, currently maintained by each individual Local Authority, are statutory, historic and fairly static, containing records of property charges which currently exist (e.g. tree preservation orders, listed building status).
Currently, each of the 326 Local Authorities across England have their own processes for maintaining a register of the existence of the Local Land Charges that affect land and property within their jurisdiction. These ‘notice’ registers are made up of paper records, microfiche, digital records, or a hybrid of record types.
This updated Prior Information Notice (the original one was published on 30 June 2015) is to highlight to the market that Land Registry intends, over the next 12 months, to be procuring services in the following areas:
1.	Quality Assurance Partner (Lot 1 in II.2)

The Quality Assurance Partner will assist Land Registry with implementing the independent Quality Assurance of data generation and migration preparations in accordance with Local Land Charges Data Digitisation Strategy and Standards

2.	Digitisation and Migration Partners (Lot 2 in II.2) 
Digitisation of existing Local Land Charges records from all Local Authorities (be they paper, microfiche, digital or hybrid) for migration to the Local Land Charges Register. It is possible that, due to the size, scope, and complexity of this work, consideration may be given to the establishment of a framework agreement.

3.	The following information is for completeness and background information only as these requirements will not be subject to calls for competition for reasons described.
•	Local Land Charges Register and Hosting for the Register. In addition to these 2 lots, Land Registry are building the Local Land Charges Register in house using an Alpha, Beta build approach. The in house team will be augmented, where required, by procuring resources from an existing UK Government framework. The hosting requirements for the Registry will also be procured from an existing UK Government framework.
•	Planning Delivery Partner. Following the PIN issued on 30 June 2015 this procurement has been completed through an open procedure. Subject to approvals the contract is anticipated to be awarded in August 2016. The Planning Delivery Partner will support Land Registry throughout the programme, bringing in capacity and capability across a range of important disciplines, including Programme management (including Delivery Milestones, overall delivery performance reporting and programme resourcing resilience), Supplier management, Procurement, Financial management, and the Provision of specialist Local Land Charges advice and support with the Local Land Charges Interim and Full Business Cases. They will work with Land Registry to initially procure, and then subsequently manage, the D and M Delivery

column58: Pewsey Health and Wellbeing Centre
column59:
Part demolition of the existing local centre including the existing swimming pool. New construction of swimming pool, Multipurpose use room, gym and changing facilities. Refurbishment of remaining structures including sports hall and new wheeled sports area. The existing services installations are to be renewed and are likely to include a PV array on the roof of the sports hall and biomass boilers.

The existing facility will be closed before works commence. There is no intention to include a phased handover of the works.

The forecast construction value of the project is £7.0m and the required construction completion date is January 2018.

A Design Team have been appointed who will take the design up to RIBA Stage 3 prior to formal tender. 

The envisaged procurement route will be Single Stage Design and Build utilising the latest JCT Design and Build form of Contract. This will be confirmed on publication of the contract notice.

The requirement is for a Construction Company to be selected, appointed and to enter into contract with Wiltshire Council to work with the council’s representatives and the current Design Team who will be novated across to the successful contractor to complete the Technical Design and to construct and handover the completed facility by the end of January 2018.

This Prior Information Notice (PIN) is not a call for competition for the purposes of Regulation 26(9) of the Public Contracts regulation 2015 — a specific call for competition for this planned procurement is likely be published by means of a contract notice in or around August 2016.

The purpose of this PIN is an early notification to the market of the Council’s intention to publish a contract notice for these services in the next few months. It is anticipated that contract will be awarded to the successful construction contractor in Autumn 2016 with services to commence immediately after and completion by the end of January 2018.

This PIN is also to advise the market of a potential market engagement event which will be confirmed on publication of the contract notice.

Following this PIN and the receipt of Expressions of Interest, it is currently the intention of the Council to follow the Restricted Procedure route under the Public Contract Regulations (aka PCR) 2015 for the appointment of the Contractor either via traditional or Design and Build.

There are no procurement documents to be completed at this time. Organisations that express interest in this PIN will be automatically contacted when the tender documents are released.

Early Market Engagement 
Wiltshire council may seek to engage with potential contractors in an early market engagement event. If this is to take place, details will be included in the contract notice

column58: Understanding employer's referrals of doctors to the General Medical Council (GMC333)
column59:
The objectives of the project are to answer the following three research questions:
a) Is there evidence that some employers' local complaints processes, escalation criteria and concern-raising cultures tend to lead to a higher proportion of complaints referred to the GMC being ones that the GMC will need to investigate.
b) Can we identify within this some promising approaches that might be transferable to other situations and if so what are these?
c) Do different approaches lead to differences in the way different groups of doctors - in terms of their roles, seniority or demographics - are engaged with, or affected by complaints or raising of concerns.

column58: UK SBS D100X 10J Cooling System
column59:
The Science and Technology Facilities Council (STFC) is building an advanced laser system for an end customer. This system will initially be built and tested at the Rutherford Appleton Laboratory, UK, before being transferred to another facility in Germany. This procurement is for a cooling system to control and maintain the temperature of the 10J laser amplifier head. 

This Contract is for a confirmed 1x cooling system with the OPTION to purchase a further cooling system over a 48 month period. 

About UK Shared Business Services 
Putting the business into shared services
UK Shared Business Services Ltd (UK SBS) brings a commercial attitude to the public sector; helping our customers improve efficiency, generate savings and modernise.
It is our vision to become the leading provider for our customers of shared business services in the UK public sector, continuously reducing cost and improving quality of business services for Government and the public sector.

Our broad range of expert services is shared by our customers. This allows our customers the freedom to focus resources on core activities; innovating and transforming their own organisations. 

Core services include Procurement, Finance, Grants Admissions, Human Resources, Payroll, ISS, and Property Asset Management all underpinned by our Service Delivery and Contact Centre teams.
UK SBS is a people rather than task focused business. It’s what makes us different to the traditional transactional shared services centre. What is more, being a not-for-profit organisation owned by its customers, UK SBS’ goals are aligned with the public sector and delivering best value for the UK taxpayer.
UK Shared Business Services Ltd changed its name from RCUK Shared Services Centre Ltd in March 2013.
Our Customers
Growing from a foundation of supporting the Research Councils, 2012/13 saw Business Innovation and Skills (BIS) transition their procurement to UK SBS and Crown Commercial Service (CSS - previously Government Procurement Service) agree a Memorandum of Understanding with UK SBS to deliver two major procurement categories (construction and research) across Government.
UK SBS currently manages £700m expenditure for its Customers, our growth projections anticipate this will rise to £1bn in 2013/14. 
Important information

From the 2nd April 2014 the Government is introducing its new Government Security Classifications (GSC) classification scheme to replace the current Government Protective Marking Scheme (GPMS). A key aspect of this is the reduction in the number of security classifications used. All potential suppliers should make themselves aware of the changes as it may impact on this Requirement. The link below to the Gov.uk website provides information on the new GSC: 
https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/government-security-classifications

Additional information: UK Shared Business Services eSourcing

As part of the strategic alliance between UK Shared Business Services Ltd (UK SBS) and Crown Commercial Service (CCS), UK SBS can use the CCS eSourcing Suite for future procurements.

If you have not yet registered on the eSourcing Suite, this can be done online at https://gpsesourcing.cabinetoffice.gov.uk  by following the link ‘Register for CCS eSourcing’.  Please note that, to register, you must have a valid DUNS number (as provided by Dun and Bradstreet) for the organisation which you are registering, who will be entering into a contract if invited to do so. 

Once you have registered on the eSourcing Suite, a registered user can express an interest for a specific procurement.  This is done by emailing ExpressionOfInterest@crowncommercial.gov.uk.  
Your email must clearly state: the name and reference for the procurement you wish to register for; the name of the registered Bidder; and the name and contact details for the registered individual sending the email.  
Crown Commercial Service will process the email and then enable the Bidder to access the procurement online via the e-Sourcing Suite.  The registered user will receive a notification email to alert them once this has been done. 
The Sourcing documents can then be accessed on the eSourcing Suite at: https://gpsesourcing.cabinetoffice.gov.uk using the instructions detailed in the Specification documents within Contracts Finder.

As a user of the e-Sourcing Suite you will have access to Emptoris email messaging service which facilitates all messages sent to you and from you in relation to any specific RFX event.  Please note it is your responsibility to access these emails on a regular basis to ensure you have sight of all relevant information.
For technical assistance on use of the e-Sourcing Suite please contact Crown Commercial Service Helpdesk : Telephone: 0345 010 3503

column58: Improving GPs' Access to Mental Health Support -NHS GP Health Service
column59:
NHS Arden and Greater East Midlands CSU (NHS AGCSU) on behalf of NHS England (referred to as the Commissioners) is inviting suitably qualified and experienced providers to deliver NHS GP Health Service.

NHS England is commissioning the NHS GP Health service to support Practitioners working in general practice who may be suffering from mental ill-health including stress and burnout and supporting those wishing to return to clinical practice after a period of ill health. It is part of a wider package of support for general practice set out in the General Practice Forward View[1] published April 2016. It is part of
the Workforce 2020 plan[2] which has been jointly established with Health Education England (HEE), the Royal College of General Practitioners (RCGP) and the British Medical Association’s (BMA) General Practitioners Committee (GPC) has three key
strands:
•improving recruitment into general practice;
•retaining doctors within general practice; and
•supporting those who wish to return to general practice.

OBJECTIVES OF THE PROCUREMENT
The NHS GP Health service (GPH) should be a nationally consistent offer across England, delivering to consistent national standards but allowing local flexibility to best support local population needs.

The GPH service delivery model has been designed with 4 main principles / strategic objectives in mind:
•	To retain a healthy workforce and support return to clinical practice after a period of sickness
•	To reduce the perception of stigma amongst GPs who may be helped presently, or in the future, through accessing mental health services
•	Maintain a visible nationally consistent offer across England
•	To promote easy and timely access the service, ensuring Service User confidence and confidentiality The Provider must deliver the service to support all these objectives and all aspects of this service specification.

The Provider will work with the Commissioner and its key partners to continue to develop the GPH Service throughout the duration of the contract. The Provider is expected to work flexibly with the  Commissioner where it is deemed appropriate to make changes to the service specification.

Anticipated timeline milestones are:
1.Contract award – Early October 2016
2.Service commencement date – 1st January 2017

Contract duration – 2.5 years with the Commissioner having the option to extend the contract for up to a further 2 years. 

Estimated Contract value excluding VAT is a range of - 2,000,000-4,000,000 GBP per annum, with an estimated total contract value excluding VAT for the contract duration of 4.5 years of a range between £9,000000-19,500,000 GBP.

TUPE does not apply.

For details of how to obtain documentation for this ITT and how to apply please see section 5 Additional information below of this Notice.

Additional information: The Contracting Authority intends to use an eTendering system in this procurement exercise.

The services to which this notice relates fall within Part B of Schedule 3, Part 10 of the Public Services Contracts Regulations 2006 (as amended) ('the Regulations').

Previous PIN notices 457923-2015 and 38435-2016 refer.

Neither the publication of this notice nor the employment of any particular terminology nor any other indication shall be taken to mean that the contracting authorities intend to hold themselves bound by any of the Regulations save those applicable to the procurement of Part B services.

Please see published documentation for further detail.


For details of how to register please see below: 
Suppliers Instructions How to Express Interest in this Tender:
1. Registration
— Register your company on the eSourcing portal (this is only required once)
— Browse to the eSourcing Portal: https://ardengemcsu.bravosolution.co.uk/web/login.html and click the link to register
— Accept the terms and conditions and click ‘continue'
— Enter your correct business and user details
— Note the user-name you chose and click ‘Save' when complete
— You will shortly receive an e-mail with your unique password (please keep this secure)

2. Express an Interest in the tender
— Login to the portal with the user-name/password
— Click the ‘ITTs Open To All Suppliers' link. (These Invitations to Tender open to any registered supplier)
— Click on the relevant ITT to access the content (itt_484 refers).
— Click the ‘Express Interest' button at the top of the page.
— This will move the ITT into your ‘My ITTs' page. (This is a secure area reserved for your projects only)
— You can now access any attachments by clicking ‘Buyer Attachments' in the ‘ITT ' Details' box

3. Responding to the tender
— Click ‘My Response' under ITT Details', you can choose to ‘Create Response' or to ‘Decline to Respond' (please give a reason if declining)
— You can now use the ‘Messages' function to communicate with the buyer and seek any clarification
— Note the deadline for completion, then follow the on-screen instructions to complete the ITT
— There may be a mixture of on-line and off-line actions for you to perform (there is detailed on-line help available)

You must then submit your reply using the ‘Submit Response' button at the top of the page.

If you require any further assistance please consult the on-line help, or contact the eTendering helpdesk.

column58: My Social Worker. Named Social Workers Local Area Pilot & Supported Self-Assessment Pilot
column59:
This notice relates to two potential requirements 1) My Social Worker Pilot 2) Supported Self-Assessment Pilot. This notice is intended to provide interested suppliers with the opportunity to gain an understanding of a potential Department of Health (DH) requirement. The attached documents are therefore draft and for information only, may change and may not fully reflect any eventual final versions.

1) My Social Worker. Named Social Workers Local Area Pilot For People With Learning Disabilities, Autism and Mental Health Conditions.

The Department of Health may ultimately seek tenders for the provision of a service to work nationally with a range of local areas as pilot sites to design and test an effective operating model for Named Social Workers for people with learning disabilities or autism who may have mental health conditions. This will require Local Areas, with support from the successful organisation to innovate and test in practice key elements including the role, intended recipients, required support, processes, outputs and outcomes. A supplier information day has been arranged for Wednesday 20th July, details on how to attend the day are provided below.

2) Supported Self-Assessment and Planning Pilots. The Department of Health may ultimately seek tenders for the provision of a service to work with a range of local areas as pilot sites to design and trial an effective operating model for Supported Self-Assessment and Planning Pilots. The project will monitor and co-ordinate a Supported Self-Assessment and Planning Pilot in up to 9 local authorities across England. 
The service shall provide:
• The coordination of the Pilot, and the provision of professional advice where any practical issues arise on a Pilot site;
• Project support within each individual local authority involved in the Pilot to ensure they have enough resource to establish and run the Pilot effectively.

The Department intends to hold a supplier engagement event on Wednesday 20th July 2016 in London for both requirements. This will involve a two-way group discussion including presentations and Q&A sessions before individual briefings are held on a one to one basis via telephone conference calls (where suppliers are unable to attend) or face to face meetings. The date and time slots will be confirmed in due course. All service providers should register their interest in attending the briefing by emailing: garry.raisbeck@dh.gsi.gov.uk no later than Wednesday 13th July 2016, providing:
1. company and contact details of the person(s) wishing to attend;
2. a single paragraph summary of your organisation's experience including whether you are a Small to Medium Enterprise (SME).
Notes of the day including all questions and answers will be made available for those who are unable to attend or dial into a briefing.

Additional information: The Department intends to hold a supplier engagement event on Wednesday 20th July 2016 in London. The evaluation of the submission will be undertaken based on individual contract requirement and the result merged to offer increased benefits where there are proven synergies or shared benefits to be gained by the council. For the benefits of contract management three contracts will be signed whether all three projects are awarded to a single contractor as a combined bid or awarded to three different contractors as individual projects. column58: Lancaster City Centre Masterplan and Investment Framework
column59:
Lancaster is one of the country’s most important historic and cultural destinations with over 2,000 years of history behind it. The city is now looking forward and is developing an ambitious vision for the next 25 years aimed at realising its potential and putting in place the infrastructure to bid for World Heritage Site and City of Culture status.

Lancaster City Council is leading a partnership of organisations committed to fully realising the economic potential of the city by developing and implementing the vision. A great deal of work has been done by the many organisations with an interest in Lancaster but much remains to be done.

We are now looking for suitably qualified consultants to pick up the many activities and opportunities existing in and around Lancaster centre and draw these together into an agreed long-term Vision for the city and an accompanying Investment Framework to turn the vision into reality. The successful consultant will evaluate Lancaster’s key strengths and highlight opportunities to raise the city’s profile and improve its attractiveness as a place to visit, live, work and invest in.

column58: ITT for The Supply of Plant Hire
column59:
Sandwell MBC Highways Services are responsible for co-ordinating plant hire throughout Sandwell. Highways Services are working with the Corporate Procurement Service in order to establish a Framework Agreement for the provision of plant hire to supply a range of plant, including compressors, rollers, plate vibrators, excavators, tippers and other specialist plant to meet the plant hire requirements of Sandwell MBC (the “Council”). Highways Services wishes to invite interested suppliers (“Tenderers”) to participate in a tender exercise in relation to the Framework Agreement. 

The Council is a member of the Black Country Purchasing Consortium, which is a partnership in procurement formed between the borough councils of Dudley, Sandwell, Walsall and Wolverhampton City Council. One of the primary objectives of the Black Country Purchasing Consortium is to establish collaborative framework agreements for the supply of goods and services that are commonly purchased across all four local authorities. It is for each individual local authority to determine if they wish to participate in / utilise each individual framework agreement.

For the purpose of this tender exercise, at the time of advertisement only the borough council of Sandwell have confirmed their intention to utilise this framework agreement. However, the borough councils of Dudley, Walsall and Wolverhampton City Council may wish to utilise it during the term of the framework agreement. 

The Council will be using the In-tend e-Tendering System for this Procurement exercise, please visit https://in-tendhost.co.uk/sandwellmbc to access the Sandwell MBC In-tend Supplier Portal.

From here you will be able to register your company, express an interest in the opportunity, and gain immediate access to the ITT and other related documents.

In Order To View the On-Line Questionnaire and Submit a Tender, you will be required to “Opt-In”.   

Please be mindful that if you are cut and pasting your question responses onto the On-Line Questionnaire that you do so from a “Notepad” document, this is due to the fact that some special characters are not accepted within the On-Line Questionnaire. 

For a Step by Step user guide to the Sandwell MBC In-tend Supplier Portal please click on the Guidance for “Suppliers” section of the website. All procurement responses must be carried out via the Sandwell MBC In-tend Supplier Portal.  

If you require further assistance in respect of the system please contact the In-tend support team on +44 844 272 8810.

Closing date: 5th August 2016 at 15:00hrs

column58: Integrated Dermatology Services - Market Engagement Event - North East Essex CCG
column59:
North East Essex Clinical Commissioning Group (The CCG) is seeking suitably qualified service providers to engage in the development of its Integrated Dermatology Service. 

The current contract for Dermatology serving the population of North East Essex will expire on 30th June 2017.  It is the CCG’s intention to tender  this service. An indicative procurement timetable will be provided during the event, however, we anticipate the new service would commence on 1st July 2017 and would be for a duration of 5years 9months.

North East Essex CCG  is taking the opportunity to review the current service specification with a view to making service improvements which will be informed by engagement with service users and providers.

The CCG also believes that market engagement is essential to inform our market knowledge, the opportunities for service integration and indeed the rationale for decisions as to the most appropriate route to market. 

The Market Engagement event will provide a further opportunity to consult with stakeholders and for prospective service providers to:-

 • Learn more about Dermatology services in North East Essex 
• Share information about services that they are able to provide or develop.

The format of the event will be a Presentation from the CCG followed by a 30-minute Q & A session. Following the Presentation, we are keen to make available individual 20-minute 1-to-1 slots with interested potential providers to answer more detailed questions and capture feedback and innovative concepts. The information gathered will be used to inform the CCG’s service model for Dermatology services and future procurement plan.


The event will be held on Monday 25th July 2016, from 9.30 am at Aspen House, Stephenson Road, Severalls Business Park, Colchester, CO4 9QR. Refreshments will be available from 9.00 am

If you wish to participate in this Pre-Tender market engagement event, please complete and e-mail the attached booking form to anthonywest2@nhs.net by 2pm on Thursday 21st July 2016.  

Please ensure that you confirm within the booking form whether or not you are interested in an individual 1-to-1 slot with the Commissioners. 

Please note – Due to limitations of space, attendance is restricted to a maximum of 2 representatives per organisation.


Please Note: Any expenditure, work or effort undertaken by you prior to any subsequent procurement is a matter solely for your own commercial judgment. The CCG reserves the right to withdraw from the process at any time or to not tender the service(s) or to tender on a different basis. In such circumstances, and in any event, The CCG and/or its advisors shall not be liable for any costs or loss of expenses whatsoever incurred by any company, agent, subsidiary or organisation that may have contributed to any proposals submitted to this notice.

column58: Minor Eye Conditions Service Market Event
column59:
Ophthalmology has been identified by City and Hackney and Islington Clinical Commissioning Group as an area that would benefit from service redesign to provide a more efficient use of resources, providing more services in a community setting and reducing pressure on urgent care and acute eye services.
Therefore, the CCGs are commissioning a Community Minor Eye Conditions Service and are looking for interested providers of this service. The service will provide assessment and treatment in the community of a number of minor eye conditions, and includes glaucoma repeat measurement and referral refinement for patients with cataracts or suspected glaucoma. The CCGs would anticipate the service to be delivered by optometrists with clinical oversight from a consultant ophthalmologist. 
The expected activity levels for the service are 3,300 (Islington and City and Hackney figures) with an approximate annual contract value of £165,000.


Commissioners are holding a market event on Thursday 28th July from 13.15-15.00 in the Hoxton Room, St Leonard’s Hospital, Nuttall Street, N1 5LZ where there will be a short presentation about the process and the service model followed by a chance to ask questions. 

Current and interested providers of eye care in Islington and City & Hackney boroughs are invited to join the event to find out more and provide any comments on how the service can link with current hospital services. 
Action: please register for the market day by confirming your attendance to clinical.procurement@nelcsu.nhs.uk. 
Pre-market event questionnaire 
Action: all providers who interested in providing the service to fill out prior to the market event (deadline 5pm 26th July). Please send completed questionaires to clinical.procurement@nelcsu.nhs.uk

procurement. This is done by emailing expressionofinterest@crowncommercial.gov.uk.
Your email must clearly state: the name and reference for the procurement you wish to register for; the
name of the registered Bidder; and the name and contact details for the registered individual sending the
email.
Crown Commercial Service will process the email and then enable the Bidder to access the procurement
online via the e-Sourcing Suite. The registered user will receive a notification email to alert them once this
has been done.
The Sourcing documents can then be accessed on the eSourcing Suite at:
https://gpsesourcing.cabinetoffice.gov.uk using the instructions detailed in the Specification documents
within Contracts Finder.
As a user of the e-Sourcing Suite you will have access to Emptoris email messaging service which facilitates
all messages sent to you and from you in relation to any specific RFX event. Please note it is your
responsibility to access these emails on a regular basis to ensure you have sight of all relevant information.
For technical assistance on use of the e-Sourcing Suite please contact Crown Commercial Service
Helpdesk : Telephone: 0345 010 3503
Training documents to support Bidders utilise Emptoris CCS eSourcing are available in the Contracts
Finder Tender documents section

column58: Healthy Steps Together- Phase 2
column59:
Purpose and details of support required
The project requires design and deployment expertise to establish a cross-disciplinary team to undertake a behavioural change design approach to understand and develop user-centred solutions to improve the health and wellbeing of communities across the specific settings of housing and schools. The project also requires the set up and management of data collection sources or identification of new sources for evaluation.
Outline of key tasks/deliverables
1.	Develop a delivery plan for the proposed scope of work and according to the specified delivery timeframe. Project management of the project delivery, engaging with site working groups and the HST Project Advisory Group to lead implementation.
•	Agreement with the HST Advisory Group on project plan and scope. As part of delivery plan identify and agree critical input required from stakeholders and project management levels and resources, at both project and site specific levels.
•	 Detail core design approach to delivery including project plan.. Agree on format of reports and specific products to be produced throughout the project duration
•	Include high-level costings, resource requirements within the limits of the project  budget 

2.	Deliver phase 2 of the Healthy Steps Together initiative in which the solutions prototyped in phase 1 (detailed in table 1) are fully implemented and evaluated for wider London learning. Objectives should include:
•	Identify and set up working groups at each site to engage  local communities and key stakeholders (including borough childhood obesity leads, Borough DPHs and CCG’s) 
•	Use these working groups and behavioural insight and design expertise to fully develop ideas, that were coproduced in phase 1 to address childhood obesity, into blueprints and implement these in the local community
•	Ensure that development of ideas are, where appropriate, linked into and make best use of existing local initiatives to make sure they are most impactful
•	Ensure ideas are developed with consideration of engaging hard to reach groups
•	Alongside the implementation of the proposed solutions/ideas, fully implement and test the transferable principles developed in phase 1 (as set out in Table 2 below) against each idea to ensure solution as impactful as possible
•	Establish a robust framework for behaviour change which works and can potentially be applied to different health challenges
•	Ensure that any tools developed are scalable for possible future delivery across broader settings and health challenges (e.g. hospitals, sporting clubs, dentists etc; smoking, alcohol)
3.	At each of the sites, the Design team will work with key users and stakeholders to undertake a process of co-development, co-delivery and evaluation of the initial solutions within agreed framework/themes ensuring that upon completion of the pilot, the solutions can be sustained.
